		<div id="post_message_1173844">
                  
                  A lot of the information with the counter spell UI would need to be user friendly and good for quick glance refrince.<br />
<br />
The spell schools would be color coded, so you would know instantly that red = nuke, green = debuff, blue = heal, stuff like that.<br />
<br />
<br />
So, the detection of color and the name of the school would be very quick to recognize, and for most spell countering check this is the only info you would get.<br />
<br />
<font color="Red">evocation</font><br />
<font color="cyan">restoration</font><br />
<font color="Lime">alteration </font> <br />
<br />
And the casting time of course, also each of those schools would have their specific icons, like a lightning bolt for evocation, a heart for restoration, and a hand for alteration.<br />
<br />
So, you would know what &quot;kind&quot; of spell is being cast very quickly.<br />
<br />
<br />
Now, if you get a critical success on your spell identification, then it would be logged in your Journal, and you would see the actual spell's icon inplace of the generic icon from it's school.<br />
<br />
You would also see the spell's name under the icon, all of this would be very easy to read, it would look like:<br />
<br />
       <font color="Red">Evocation</font> (schools name color coded on top)<br />
         (name of spell if critical)<br />
         ______   <br />
         I cast I<br />
         I time I<br />
         I_____I<br />
 The above icon would display &quot;?&quot; if check 1, school's icon if check 2, specific spell's icon if critical check 3 succeeds.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
That would be a simple, user friendly display that even the simplest of players would be able to pick up on quickly. Red means its gona harm you, blue means its trying to heal, green means its trying to debuff.<br />
<br />
Now, if you wanted to be very careful and make sure you are countering the nuke that you want, and if your skill is high enough to get a good chance at seeing the specific name and icon of the spell, then that would be more than a quick glance, but that would be part of &quot;mastering&quot; the class would be the ability to quickly decide when or when not to counter a fully identified spell.
                  
		</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
